[[File:Weidbuche01.jpg|thumb|Pasture beech with 13 trunks. On closer inspection, one realizes that what, at first sight, seem to be "branches" are in reality individual trunks.]] The '''Pasture beech''' ({{lang-de|Weidbuche}}) is a particular species or growth habit of the [[fagus sylvatica|beech]] which developed in the [[Black Forest]], because the young trees growing on [[pasture]]s or in [[wood pasture|pastoral forests]] were nibbled by the grazing animals, above all cows and goats, i.e. their leaves and branches were eaten and, as a consequence, they have no main trunk and grow bushy.<ref>[http://www.lubw.baden-wuerttemberg.de/servlet/is/36652 Weidbuchen im Schwarzwald und ihre Entstehung durch Verbiß des Wälderviehs] (Pasture beeches in the Black Forest and their formation due to nibbling animals grazing in the pastoral forests), {{ISBN|3-88251-121-4}}</ref>
In the [[Southern Black Forest]] 1600 places were found where pasture beeches are growing.<ref>Southern Black Forest Nature Park: [http://www.naturpark-suedschwarzwald.de/mensch/kulturlandschaft/weidbuchen Weidbuchen]</ref>
